    "body": "> Ah, wow didn't realize geth had gotten that ridiculous!\r\n\r\nTo be fair geth **is not** ridiculous. Its code base has proven solid and the fact still holds >80% of network nodes share tells something. The fact is getting slower and slower (like **any other** ethereum node software) is due to the protocol design which does not scale well and, of course, the ever growing number of smart contracts transactions can interact with. In addition geth has followed a design pattern which is very orthodox to the original Yellow paper. Kudos to @AlexeyAkhunov for having rethought how to persist chain data internally.\r\n\r\nBesides, though we renamed to Erigon to state our difference, there probably wouldnt' be any Erigon if it wasn't for geth.\r\n\r\n> I have a 4GHz 8 core CPU being used at 20% for most of the 7/18 state syncing phase. I was wondering if that could be utilized more heavily as well as if there was room to offload some aspect to GPU processor its RAM - ultimately to speed things up. Speed up processing time by a few hundred percent, decreasing time by 75%\r\n\r\nTaking advantage of full computation capacity of your hardware would be nice to have: unfortunately the rules of the chain make it either impossible or heavily limit this. Multicore processing is possible when **parallel computation is possible** which, in most of stages, actually isn't. Basically every processed block needs data from the previous one(s) process hence linear computation is the only way to go. Besides most of operations are IO intensive rather than computation intensive: parallelization of IO intensive ops generally worsen performances.\r\nUsage of GPU resources would then add a lot of boilerplate code only to handle different types of chips (AMD/OpenCL vs NVIDIA/CUDA) with very arguable benefits: GPUs are good at parallel tasks (which we don't have).\r\n",
